# CSS: nested block classes

Use **one root block class** per component and **short child class names** scoped with selectors. Do not build BEM-style compound names on every node.

## Naming

| Role | Class | Selector example |
|------|--------|------------------|
| Block (root) | `button`, `panel`, `page` | `.button` |
| State on root | `active`, `disabled`, `open` | `.button.active`, `.panel.open` |
| Child | `content`, `label`, `inner` | `.button > .content > .label` |

- **Do not** use `block__element`, `block__element--modifier`, or repeated prefixes like `button__active__content__inner`.
- **Do** add state as a **second class on the root**: `className={["button", active && "active"].filter(Boolean).join(" ")}`.
- **Do** keep child `className` values short (`content`, `label`); scope them in CSS under the block.

## CSS

Colocate styles in the component’s `index.css`. Prefer direct-child selectors when structure is fixed:

```css
/* ❌ BAD */
.button__active .button__active__content .button__active__content__inner { }

/* ✅ GOOD */
.button.active > .content > .inner { }
.button > .content { }
.button > .label { }
```

Contextual overrides use ancestor blocks, not renamed children:

```css
/* ✅ GOOD */
.panel .button { }
.page > .content { }
```

## TSX

```tsx
/* ❌ BAD */
<div className="button__content">
  <span className="button__content__inner" />

/* ✅ GOOD */
<div className="content">
  <span className="inner" />
```

Reference: `src/components/Button/` (`button`, `active`, `> .content`, `> .label`).
